From the latest test results this year, we can see that language is the top position of the league table with the highest passing marks in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who study a foreign language get an A Plus.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS member schools, showed that 72 percent of students earned an A Plus in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who learned German, 69 percent of those who learned French and 63 percent who learned Spanish also got an A.
This suggests that independent schools in Scotland support foreign language as an important skill that will certainly be required by children and adolescents in the future.
Today the languages, as a choice of subjects, are held in the same standard as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the modern school curriculum and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK’s Employment and Skills Service in 2014 found that of several reasons why employers should continue to struggle to fill vacancies, 17 percent of the reason is a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly encouraged to prepare young people for their future careers.
With the growing number of job opportunities requiring language skills, these skills are important in a globalized world.
Whatever a person’s career choice, if they have already learned a second language, in the future they will feel the real benefit of having this kind of lifelong skill.
Being able to communicate directly with residents from foreign countries will automatically make a multilingualist superior in the competition.
According to a YouGov poll of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent of them did not speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation and French became the only language spoken in a two-digit percentage, which is 15 percent.
