Red Tide: Low concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
Recent reports from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission show a general decline in Red Tide concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, uneven buildup conditions were reported from areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – which signal a decrease in concentration.
A collection of Red Tide extends approximately 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinellas to the south Lee area.
Groups can be found about 10 miles off the coast of the Hillsborough area, but on some sites relative to last week.
Red Tide has also been observed in the Pasco region.
Moderate concentrations on or off the coast of the Pinellas region have been reported in the past week, low to high concentrations off the coast of the Hillsborough region, background to high concentrations in the Manatee region, background to high concentrations on or off the coast of the Sarasota region, background to moderate concentrations in the Charlotte region, low to high concentrations on or off the coast of the Collier region of the Lee, and Lee region.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported from Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier regions.
There have been no reports of respiratory irritation in Northwest Florida over the past week.
